<DOC><DOCNO> AP880608-0088 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0704EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Obit-Harty 1stLd-Writethru   06-08 0258</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Obit-Harty, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0593,0263</SECOND><HEAD>British Talk-Show Host Dies</HEAD><NOTE>EDS: SUBS 7th graf, `The former...' to CORRECT `him' to `her.'</NOTE><DATELINE>LEEDS, England (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Russell Harty, a writer and broadcasterwho became one of Britain's top television talk-show hosts, diedearly today, a hospital said. He was 54.   Harty, who suffered from liver failure caused by hepatitis,underwent surgery for internal bleeding when his conditiondeteriorated over the weekend, said a statement from St. JamesUniversity Hospital.   He underwent further surgery overnight and died at 4:30 a.m. inthe operating room, the statement said.   Harty was rushed unconscious to the hospital in this northernEngland city on May 3. He regained consciousness after five days ina grade four coma, the deepest known, but remained in criticalcondition.   Harty immediately asked doctors to express his thanks tothousands of his fans who had inundated the hospital with get-wellcards and messages of concern.   Published reports said Harty apparently contracted hepatitis, aninflammation of the liver, while making a television series on atour of Europe earlier this year. He was treated for hepatitis inearly April and discharged to convalesce.   The former English and drama schoolteacher had a lugubrious anddisarming manner on television. His interview subjects ranged fromPrime Minister Margaret Thatcher to rock stars. American rock starGrace Jones once struck him across the head because she thought hewas ignoring her during a TV interview.   After success as a director and producer, Harty launched his ownhugely successful talk show, ``Russell Harty Plus,'' in 1973.</TEXT></DOC>